<DOC><DOCNO> AP890302-0079 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0901EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0507 03-02 0686</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0701</SECOND><HEAD>Late-Winter Storm Hits Pacific Northwest</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with airport still closed earlytoday, one traffic fatality, other detail. PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Thesnow ...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A late-winter storm brought heavy snow to the Pacific Northwestearly this morning, and rain and thunderstorms were scattered acrossmuch of the South.   Up to half a foot of snow fell Wednesday evening in the Seattlearea, closing the Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, cancelingschool today and snarling traffic. At least one traffic fatality wasblamed on the storm.   ``Right now we have a half-inch of slush over ice in some areasand up to an inch or more of snow over ice, no braking at all,''said Rick Smith, airport fire chief. ``We're continuing to plow therunways and working to try and get them cleared.''   The airport remained closed near daybreak today, but officialshoped to open it later in the day.   Seattle and Tacoma public schools closed.   It was the second severe snowstorm of the season for westernWashington and Oregon, where any snow is noteworthy and even a fewinches can paralyze urban traffic.   ``It's not supposed to do this anymore,'' said Susan Thornton,spokeswoman for the Snohomish County Public Works Department inEverett.   The snow also reduced visibility and hampered traffic in northernOregon, where up to a foot was expected to fall.   Winter storm warnings were in effect for much of Idaho, Oregon,northwest Washington and higher elevations of central and northernCalifornia and west central Nevada. Snow advisories were posted forthe remainder of Washington, north central Oregon and the IdahoPanhandle.   Snow also was falling across the country's northern tier from thePacific Northwest to the Great Lakes, but accumulations outside ofOregon and Washington were mostly no more than an inch.   Rain fell in much of California, southern Oregon and southwestIdaho.   Thunderstorms continued across the Florida Peninsula while rainstretched from South Carolina to northern Florida, across thecentral Gulf Coast and eastern Texas.   Today's forecast called for snow in the upper Great Lakes,central Minnesota, Iowa, South Dakota, northern Wyoming, Montana,northern Idaho and western Washington. Rain was expected in the restof the Pacific Northwest, Nevada and all but southeast California.Rain and thunderstorms were predicted for much of the South fromsouthern portions of Virginia and West Virginia to much of Florida,and across to the lower Mississippi Valley and eastern Texas.   Highs were forecast to be in the single digits from Montana toMinnesota; in the teens and 20s from the northern Rockies across theremainder of the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley to theGreat Lakes, northern New York state and northern New England; the30s and 40s from central New England to North Carolina, the OhioValley, Missouri, northern Kansas, southern Wyoming and the PacificNorthwest; the 50s and 60s from South Carolina to northern Florida,the Tennessee Valley, the southern Plains, southern Rockies,southern Plateau and all but southeast California; and the 80s incentral and southern Florida and the lower Texas Gulf Coast. Highselsewhere were expected to be in the 70s.   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 24 degrees below zero atHibbing, Minn., to 74 degrees at Key West, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 44 cloudy; Boston 24 windy; Buffalo 13 partlycloudy; Charleston, S.C., 47 foggy; Cincinnati 26 partly cloudy;Cleveland 19 fair; Detroit 13 fair; Miami 71 foggy; New York 29partly cloudy; Philadelphia 26 fair; Pittsburgh 20 fair; Portland,Maine, 22 fair; Washington 32 fair.   _Central: Bismarck -4 fair; Chicago 19 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth48 cloudy; Denver 27 foggy; Des Moines 17 snow; Indianapolis 24cloudy; Kansas City 29 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul -1 cloudy;Nashville 33 fair; New Orleans 57 cloudy; St. Louis 31 cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 39 fair; Anchorage 19 cloudy; Las Vegas 62cloudy; Los Angeles 54 rain; Phoenix 63 cloudy; Salt Lake City 49windy; San Diego 55 cloudy; San Francisco 50 rain; Seattle 28 snow.   _Canada: Montreal 14 fair; Toronto 10 partly cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>